WHEN TO BOOK YOUR MAKEUP ARTIST✨

Do not wait to book your makeup artist and hairstylist! 

As soon as you have your fiancé, bridal party, wedding date, and ceremony time confirmed, it’s time to secure your beauty vendors.

I typically recommend booking your makeup artist at least one year in advance, with many clients reserving my services a year and a half to two years ahead of time.

Regrettably, this crucial information is sometimes overlooked during wedding planning, and I’ve had October brides reaching out in April of the same year, hoping to secure my services 😌

My September/October schedule is usually fully booked well in advance. It’s disheartening to see brides struggling to find beauty vendors so late in the game, and I fear they might have to settle for any available artist - a situation I wouldn’t wish upon anyone.

To avoid this, my best advice is to book your beauty vendors early on in the wedding planning process. 

How you look and feel on such a memorable day is so incredibly important. 

You deserve the perfect artist for you, not just someone you had to settle for. So, don’t hesitate and secure your dream beauty team now! ✨

𝗕𝗘𝗛𝗜𝗡𝗗 𝗠𝗬 𝑺𝑰𝑮𝑵𝑨𝑻𝑼𝑹𝑬 𝗕𝗥𝗜𝗗𝗔𝗟 𝗚𝗟𝗔𝗠✨

Over the years I have curated the perfect bridal glam look that is now my signature.  It's a timeless, seamless look that radiates pure elegance, and I tailor it to accentuate your individual beauty.

✨𝗕𝗮𝘀𝗲 | medium to full coverage and seamless. I ensure that your skin looks cohesive with no harsh lines and effortlessly blended from your gorgeous face to you décolleté area locked in for all day wear. 

✨𝗖𝗼𝗻𝘁𝗼𝘂𝗿 | seamlessly blended contour to add depth and warmth to the face. 

✨𝗕𝗹𝘂𝘀𝗵 | a romantic peachy/pink pop of color.

✨𝗛𝗶𝗴𝗵𝗹𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 |  soft glass-like pop of luminance dancing along the cheekbones, inner corner of the eyes, above the Cupid’s bow, top of brow bone and very subtly on the nose. 

✨𝗘𝘆𝗲𝘀 | softly defined with a smudged/smoked out soft wing. Neutral browns with a hint of soft peach adding depth to the outer corners of the eyes. A subtle cut crease accentuating the inner corner with the perfect balance of shimmer on the lid fading to a pop of inner corner highlight. Lashes that add the perfect balance of volume, length and curl without over-powering the eye. 

✨𝗟𝗶𝗽𝘀 | subtly overlined, topped with the perfectly romantic neutral - peachy/pink shade. A lip touch-up is always included in your touch-up kit. 

✨𝗕𝗿𝗼𝘄𝘀 | softly defined. Brows are such a unique and personal preference I can style them any way desired, whether soft and brushed up, or defined and carved out. 

✨𝗕𝗼𝗱𝘆 𝗚𝗹𝗼𝘄 | the ideal amount of luminance along your décolleté area, shoulders and arms without looking oily. 

Although this is my 𝒔𝒊𝒈𝒏𝒂𝒕𝒖𝒓𝒆 bridal glam, we can absolutely customize this look to your unique desires, changing the lip, blush or eyeshadow colors is an easy change 🤍

#Throwback - Vintage even. Cosmetology school circa 2006 

One of the most frequent questions I get is, "How long have you been doing makeup?" Well, the surprising answer is almost 18 years 🤯

At the young age of 18, I embarked on my journey as a cosmetologist. But even before that, I was the go-to girl for doing my friends' makeup for dances and special occasions. My foundation in makeup artistry was further enriched through the various theater productions I was a part of during the transition from high school into college.

My heart always leaned towards makeup artistry, and it's been my enduring passion, even more than hairstyling. It didn't take me long to realize that this is where I wanted to focus my career. 

This decision has since paved the way for a highly successful and deeply fulfilling career spanning nearly two decades, and I am forever thankful that that girl rocking those duck lips followed her dreams 🤍🥹

During the consultation of Mary’s 1 on 1 lesson I determined that she is a Deep Autumn.  All lessons come with a color analysis to help you know what colors look best on you, as well as product recommendations. 

Deep Autumn is a unique blend that marries the warm, rich hues of autumn with the dark, intense shades of winter, according to the 12-season system of color analysis.

Deep Autumn is classified in the following ways: warm hue, dark value, neutral chroma.

Warm hue – the undertone is always red, but various overtones of gray or violet may give a cooler or occasional blue appearance, causing confusion when determining the difference between deep autumn and deep winter.

Dark value – this is one of the seasons characterized by depth and darkness of color. This is one of the defining characteristics and holds true for all deep autumns.

Neutral chroma – there is some variation here. Some deep autumn types may exhibit much more muting as seen in the need for grayer toned colors, while others may be able to handle more brightness.

Deep Autumn shares a unique trait with its sister season, Deep Winter: both are characterized by darker values. While Deep Autumn can embrace somewhat richer colors due to its proximity to Deep Winter, it’s essential to maintain a low overall contrast level to align with its own characteristics of neutral to slightly muted chroma and medium-to-dark value.

During the consultation of Jennifer's Duo lesson, I determined that she is a Light Summer. All lessons come with a color analysis to help you know what colors look best on you, as well as product recommendations.

Light summer is similar to light spring, although summer needs cool tones. These individuals are very, very light compared to the rest of the population.

The skin is likely to be light ivory or cool beige. The eyes will typically be blue or green, and on the lighter end of the spectrum. A soft gray eye is also possible in light summer.

Hair is the in the blonde color family, from light platinum to dark blonde, and and will have no gold or red highlights. The hair may occasionally be light brown.

The features are overall similar in depth, with none of the features standing out above the rest. Light summer has an icy coolness to their features and stands out when framed by pastel shades.

For the eyes, choose light neutrals such as silvery white, icy pink, soft ivory, and dusky blue. Dark colors should be no deeper than medium taupe. Accent colors could be blush, soft plum, or mauve.

For the cheeks, neutral cool shades of sand, soft pink, and rose are wonderful to gently accentuate the gentle features of light summer.

Nude lips are a winner for light summer, along with blush and cotton candy. A bold lip for such a light season would be mauve or rose, and deep bubblegum substitutes for red.

Avoid warm tones like brown or orange red lipstick, copper and yellow eyeshadows, and bronze cheek colors. Light summer should also stay away from dark makeup colors.

Celebrities that are light summers: Naomi Watts, Amy Poehler, Cate Blanchett, Gwyneth Paltrow.
